Introduction to Collections and List in Java

In Java, the Collection Framework is used to store and manage groups of objects.

It provides ready-to-use classes and interfaces that make working with data much easier.

What is Collection?

A Collection is a group of objects (like a container).

Java provides the Collection interface, which is the root of the collection hierarchy.

Main features:

dynamic size (can grow and shrink)
built-in methods (add, remove, search, etc.)
works with generics for type safety
Common Collection Types

Some of the most commonly used collections are:

List → ordered collection
Set → unique elements only
Queue → elements processed in order
List Interface

List is one of the most popular collection types.

It represents an ordered collection of elements, where:

elements are stored in a specific order
duplicates are allowed
elements can be accessed by index
Common List Implementations
1. ArrayList
based on a dynamic array
fast access by index
slower when inserting/removing in the middle
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");

System.out.println(list.get(0)); // Apple
2. LinkedList
based on a linked structure
faster insert/remove operations
slower access by index
List<String> list = new LinkedList<>();
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");
Common List Methods

Some useful methods:

add(element) → add element
remove(index) → remove element
get(index) → get element
size() → number of elements
contains(value) → check if element exists
Key Differences
ArrayList	LinkedList
Fast access (get)	Slower access
Slower insert/remove	Faster insert/remove
Uses array	Uses linked nodes
Summary
Collections help manage groups of objects
List is an ordered collection
ArrayList is good for reading data
LinkedList is better for frequent insert/remove operations
